<DOC><DOCNO> AP880811-0210 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 2221EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-11 0505</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0519</SECOND><HEAD>East Swelters In Heat, Humidity</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Much of the nation broiled under 90-degree weather Thursday,with the East enduring high humidity as well. Remnants of tropicalstorm Beryl soaked the Louisiana and Texas coasts.   The temperature in Philadelphia climbed to 90 degrees Thursdayafternoon for the 44th time this summer. The summer of 1983 heldthe previous record with 41 days of 90 degrees or higher in 110years of recorded weather history.   The oppressive heat and humidity stretched from southern NewEngland to Maryland and over much of Indiana and Illinois. The heatbrought pleas from an Albany, N.Y., utility for customers to cutback their electricity use to avoid blackouts.   Six inches of rain fell Thursday at Cushing, Texas, and 2 to 4inches of rain fell in parts of northwest Louisiana Thursdaymorning. Flash flood warnings were posted in northeast Texas.   In the Houston area, thunderstorms produced heavy rain earlyThursday afternoon. Over an inch of rain fell in the northern partof Harris County and street flooding was reported.   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were scattered from thesouth Atlantic coastal states across the central and southernAppalachians to the Great Lakes region. Scattered showers alsodeveloped over New England.   Lightning struck and killed a boater in northwest Minnesota. InWisconsin, wind gusts to 50 mph and pea-size hail was reported atRipon in the east-central part of the state. Thunderstorm windsdowned trees at Eden, Wis.   Thunderstorms developed around midday in northwest Arizona andsouthwest Utah. Thunderstorm gusts reached 63 mph at Milford, Utah.   Skies were mostly sunny Thursday afternoon over the northern andcentral Plains. Temperatures reached over 100 degrees in portionsof South Dakota.   Skies were sunny in the Pacific Northwest where temperatureswere on the pleasant side. It was 65 degrees in Seattle at noon.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 104 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.,and Phoeniz, Ariz. Thursday's low in the nation was 35 degrees atGunnison, Colo.   Record-high temperatures were set in Beckley, W. Va., 88;Binghamton, N.Y., 87; Buffalo, N.Y., 92; and Bridgeport, Conn., 92.   Friday's forecast was for showers and thunderstorms scatteredfrom the Gulf Coast northward to eastern Kansas, southern Missouri,the Ohio Valley and eastern portions of the Great Lakes region.   Showers and thunderstorms were predicted for southwest Missouri,eastern Oklahoma and western Arkansas. Widely scattered showers andthunderstorms were forecast for portions of New England and the NewYork City area. Widely scattered thunderstorms were also expectedto develop from the northern Great Lakes to North Dakota, and fromthe Rockies to the mountains of Arizona.   High temperatures were forecast in the upper 80s and 90s acrossmost of the nation; in the lower 80s from northern Michigan tonorthern Minnesota; in the 70s and low 80s over the PacificNorthwest and along the Pacific Coast. Temperatures between 95 and110 degrees were predicted for the Dakotas and in the desertSouthwest.</TEXT></DOC>